As far as KEI and it being overpowered for casters under a certain level, with todays gear available to melee that are faster and harder hitting weps and better armor, the game dynamics have changed and the mobs in new expansions are have more hits, so unless they have changed the amount of mana you gain at each level for start up wizards since eq release, I think KEI and other mana regen spells are sort of a balance and makes the game more fun for new players to stick, as it should be fun and not work.<br>
<br>
Scinder <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=necridious>Necridious</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 286<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/18/03 4:37:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25485.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://personal.atl.bellsouth.net/atl/d/a/dastorys/Pictures/Nec-60x60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Warning!!-Dont forget to Feed </span><hr size=1> I have no problem with KEI being properly level restricted so long as they address the problem that KEI fixes at that level.  Twinked Melee easily do more damage than even a very twinked caster of the same level because of the disparity between gear and spells.  I believe this disparity should be corrected so that the classes recieve equal benefits from their gear.<br>
<br>
<br>
Melee get weapons and armor as guild quests.  This makes sense, as weapons and armor are the primary things those classes are after--- this is exceedinly true to the un-twinked melee.  When your looking at a Dragoon Dirk as an upgrade to your current stabber, and mourning that it's an incredible 40pp plunge into the bank, those guild quests are very hard, but they are at least (to them) worth it.<br>
<br>
Casters, on the other hand get weapons and armor from their guild quests..../boggle.  In the Pre-luclin era, this was to be expected, because there was nothing short of xp that could improve what a caster does, which is casting spells.  Now, with the introduction of spell foci and Flowing Thought items, there is something to help the lowbie caster.  Level 1, and possibly level 2 foci should be questable at your home guild.  A small amount of Flowing Thought should be questable too, for Higher level(30'ish) casters.  This is when KEI starts to become necessary to even hope to keep up with a group of average equiped melee.  The current guild quests for casters offers a few Int items(good) but very little else that is worth the time and effort even to a caster that is untwinked.<br>
<br>
I have no problem at all with balancing through gear, but there needs to be equity.  Armor and weapons do wonders for a melee, but do very little for us.  In truth, it has happened that people have banked or even destroyed end game items for lack of foci effects.  These effects are integral to what we do, so we want them very badly.  We should be able to get starting levels of these abilities at the starting levels.  I can not think of a single level 1 focus item that was retroactivly fitted with focus effects that is actually useful for the level that can reasonably aquire the item--most of those items would be a challenge for a group in the high 20's, yet they don't work on spells above 20.  Level 1 effects should be obtainable at the latest the early teens so the item see's some play before becoming obsolete.<br>
<br>
Also, since spells you can cast are determined by level, there should be buffs or items that raise your casting level.  If a level 1 melee can equip a Fine Steel Sword (not obtainable as loot till mid teens) and use it to it's full effectiveness, then a level 1 similarly twinked caster should be casting spells from a circle or 2 up as well.  Most will consider this a bit over the top, but unless they level restrict every item in game to slightly lower than the level it's obtainable, then they should make spells usable below their normal level as well. <p><br>
